				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">From what I've heard, audio data ($40xx registers) is usually buffered in RAM, and changes in audio are written to the buffer from least priority to greatest priority, and then the buffer is written to the actual registers. It makes it easy to do sound effects with background music this way. In the majority of NES games sound effects have priority over the music becuase a short sound effect stopping a channel from playing for less than a second usually isn't noticeable. Usually, when more than one sound effect tries to occur, and the sound effects share the same channel, the sound effect that occurs latest is played.</div>

